Absolutely—let’s fix that left drift. Nine times out of ten it’s one of these: mismatched sensor scaling/thresholds, swapped sensor polarity, or a small motor imbalance. Here’s a quick, targeted plan you can run in 10–15 minutes.

Step 1: Sanity-check raw sensor values
- Goal: confirm black < white (or vice versa) and see if L/R are biased.
- Paste this minimal reader, hold sensors over white, then over the line, and note the numbers.

Setup snippet
- Add to setup:
  Serial.begin(115200);

- In loop (temporary):
  int lRaw = analogRead(A0); // adjust pins
  int rRaw = analogRead(A1);
  Serial.print("L:"); Serial.print(lRaw);
  Serial.print("  R:"); Serial.print(rRaw);
  Serial.println();
  delay(100);

What you want to see
- On white: both high and similar (e.g., L≈800, R≈820).
- On black: both lower and similar (e.g., L≈250, R≈260).
If black reads higher than white, your polarity is flipped—fix by inverting comparisons or normalization.

Step 2: Set proper per‑sensor thresholds
- Don’t use one global threshold if the sensors differ. Use one per sensor:
  tL = (Lwhite + Lblack)/2
  tR = (Rwhite + Rblack)/2

Patch example
int tL = (lWhite + lBlack)/2;
int tR = (rWhite + rBlack)/2;
bool leftBlack  = (lRaw < tL);   // or > tL if polarity is reversed
bool rightBlack = (rRaw < tR);

Step 3: Fix normalization and offset so “center = zero”
- Normalize each sensor with its own min/max (or white/black pair), then compute error. Subtract a small offset so small L/R bias doesn’t cause constant turning.

Add this calibration once at startup
// Fill these from your quick measurements:
int lWhite=0, lBlack=0, rWhite=0, rBlack=0;
// After you record them:
int lMin = min(lWhite, lBlack), lMax = max(lWhite, lBlack);
int rMin = min(rWhite, rBlack), rMax = max(rWhite, rBlack);
int offset = ((rWhite - rBlack) - (lWhite - lBlack)) / 2; // L/R bias on white

Normalize to “blackness” 0..1000 (higher = more black)
int normL = map(constrain(lRaw, lMin, lMax), lMin, lMax, 0, 1000);
int normR = map(constrain(rRaw, rMin, rMax), rMin, rMax, 0, 1000);
// If black gives lower raw, invert so higher = more black:
normL = 1000 - normL;
normR = 1000 - normR;

Compute error with deadband
int error = (int)normL - (int)normR - offset; // positive if more black under left
if (abs(error) < 8) error = 0; // deadband to kill tiny drift

Then your PD correction stays the same. If your motor mixing expects the opposite sign, just flip error = -error.

Step 4: Check motor trim
- Run both motors forward at the same PWM (no line following). If it drifts left, your left motor is weaker. Add a small trim:
int leftTrim = +5;   // increase until it drives straight
int rightTrim = 0;
leftSpeed  += leftTrim;
rightSpeed += rightTrim;

Quick “why it turns left” cheatsheet
- Right sensor reads a bit higher than left on white → error stays positive → correction makes left motor slower → constant left turn. Fix with per‑sensor scaling + offset/deadband.
- Polarity flipped (black reads higher than white) on one or both sensors → logic fights itself. Fix by inverting comparisons/normalization.
- Global threshold set too low/high → one sensor always “black,” the other “white.” Use per‑sensor thresholds from real measurements.

